    • setNumeralBase

      public static void setNumeralBase(com.github.tommyettinger.digital.Base base)
      Sets the numeral system, also called radix or base, used by some methods here to encode numbers. This is most likely to be used with Base.scrambledBase(Random) to obfuscate specific numbers, such as random seeds, put into readable JSON files. The methods this affects are mostly related to registering EnhancedRandom and its implementations, RandomXS128, and AtomicLong. If this hasn't been called, the default this uses is Base.BASE10, because it is the most human-readable.
      Parameters:
      base - a non-null Base system

    • areFloatsLegible

      public static boolean areFloatsLegible()
      Gets the status of whether this will write float and double items using Base.general(float) (when true) or Base.signed(int) (when false). Sometimes one option will produce smaller output, and sometimes the other will. If this is false, then there is a maximum length a float or double will use (in chars). If this is true, then floats and doubles will always print in base-10, and only use scientific notation for very large or very small numbers (determined by distance from 0.0), but the maximum length is larger.
      Returns:
      true if this is writing floats in a human-readable way, or false if writing floats in a compact way

    • isAddClassTags

      public static boolean isAddClassTags()
      Gets the status of whether this will add short class tags when registering classes. If true (the default), this will use very short class tags. If false, this will use the normal Json behavior of package-qualified class names, which can be quite long.
      Returns:
      true if this is currently set to add class tags when registering classes, or false otherwise

    • setAddClassTags

      public static void setAddClassTags(boolean addClassTags)
      If true, this will call Json.addClassTag(String, Class) to register a very short name when registering most classes. If false, registering classes will not register class tags. Using short class tags can impede readability, but if users are expected to either not see raw JSON files or not care about class entries in them, then using short tags saves a lot of file size. This is especially useful for games that transmit JSON over a network. The default for this, if not yet called, is true (it will use short tags).
      Parameters:
      addClassTags - if true, this will use short class tags instead of long names with packages for classes

    • registerAtomicLong

      public static void registerAtomicLong(@NonNull com.badlogic.gdx.utils.Json json)
      Registers AtomicLong with the given Json object, so AtomicLong can be written to and read from JSON. This primarily matters if you intend to read and/or write Random objects or their subclasses without registering a custom serializer for them. Although the EnhancedRandom implementations in jdkgdxds have custom serializers here already, and don't need this method to be called, other classes that extend Random are likely to need this if you ever run on Java 16 or higher.
      Surprisingly, this method is compatible with GWT, even though most concurrent code doesn't work there.
      Parameters:
      json - a libGDX Json object that will have a serializer registered

    • registerAlternateRandom

      public static void registerAlternateRandom(@NonNull com.badlogic.gdx.utils.Json json)
      Registers AlternateRandom with the given Json object, so AlternateRandom can be written to and read from JSON. Note that AlternateRandom is not a juniper EnhancedRandom, and so cannot be deserialized to an EnhancedRandom field. It is also almost exactly the same as PasarRandom, so you might want to just prefer PasarRandom if you depend on juniper anyway because of this library.

    • registerEnhancedRandom

      public static void registerEnhancedRandom(@NonNull com.badlogic.gdx.utils.Json json)
      Registers EnhancedRandom with the given Json object, so EnhancedRandom can be written to and read from JSON. This also registers DistinctRandom, LaserRandom, TricycleRandom, FourWheelRandom, Xoshiro256StarStarRandom, Xoshiro128PlusPlusRandom, Xoshiro256MX3Random, Xoroshiro128StarStarRandom, StrangerRandom, TrimRandom, WhiskerRandom, RomuTrioRandom, ChopRandom, Xoshiro128PlusPlusRandom, MizuchiRandom, ScruffRandom, AceRandom, GoldenQuasiRandom, VanDerCorputQuasiRandom, LowChangeQuasiRandom, TupleQuasiRandom, and KnownSequenceRandom, plus AtomicLong because some subclasses of Random need it. This does not register DistributedRandom or the wrappers ReverseWrapper and ArchivalWrapper, but registerDistributedRandom(Json), registerReverseWrapper(Json), and registerArchivalWrapper(Json) call this method instead (the first of those also calls registerDistribution(Json)).
      Abstract classes aren't usually serializable like this, but because each of the EnhancedRandom serializers uses a specific format shared with what this uses, and that format identifies which class is used, it works here.
      Parameters:
      json - a libGDX Json object that will have a serializer registered

    • registerRandomXS128

      public static void registerRandomXS128(@NonNull com.badlogic.gdx.utils.Json json)
      Registers RandomXS128 with the given Json object, so RandomXS128 can be written to and read from JSON. Note that RandomXS128 is not a jdkgdxds EnhancedRandom, and so registering this won't allow you to read RandomXS128 objects from EnhancedRandom fields. This serializer is here to reduce the hassle when you do want to serialize a RandomXS128, because on Java 16 and higher, RandomXS128 would need some extra steps for Json to be able to read some fields from it.
      Parameters:
      json - a libGDX Json object that will have a serializer registered
